SIMPLE: liquefaction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Liquefaction
<hw>Liq`ue*fac"tion</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧k`w⟦esl⟧*f⟦acr⟧k"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>liquefactio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>liqu⟦eacute⟧faction</ets>. See <er>Liquefy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act or operation of making or becoming liquid; especially, the
conversion of a solid into a liquid by the sole agency of
heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being liquid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem. Physics)</fld> <def>The act, process, or
method, of reducing a gas or vapor to a liquid by means of cold or
pressure; <as>as, the <ex>liquefaction</ex> of oxygen or
hydrogen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liquefiable</ent>⟦br⟧
